<TEXT>
on a windswept hill fragrant with 
prairie sage the daughter of a utah sheep rancher passed 
photographs of nuclear bomb blasts to the kazakhs crowded around 
her eyes widened 
we have seen such mushroom clouds from here too said a 
grizzled man in this central asia ranch town 
just like janet gordons hometown of cedar city utah karaul is 
125 miles downwind from the spot where the government routinely 
tests nuclear bombs underground 
mrs gordon 300 other foreign antinuclear activists and the 
people of karaul on sunday shared stories of death and disease they 
blame on radiation caused by the testing they were taking part in 
a fourday conference of antinuclear activists from 21 countries 
atmospheric testing was conducted by the americans and soviets 
until it was banned under a bilateral treaty in 1963 some 
radiation may have drifted across the border from aboveground 
testing in china until 1980 
my father died one kazakh in an embroidered moslem cap said 
to mrs gordon 
under the old mans banner which read we are nuclear 
victims too a young mother grasped her little boys shoulder 
my son was sick until he was four years old she said he 
could not walk without falling down 
i came to kazahkstan to meet people like you mrs gordon 
replied 
on the central asian steppe similar to areas of nevada near the 
us test zone activists traded fears research and political 
strategy with local residents who in just one year have been 
transformed from silent victims to successful protesters 
soviet activists formed the nevadasemipalatinsk antinuclear 
movement named for test sites in the two countries they exerted 
enough pressure that the soviet government has not conducted an 
underground nuclear blast at semipalatinsk since october 
soviet authorities have not agreed to a moratorium but the 
activists meeting apparently had toplevel approval since the 
zone next to the test range is normally closed to foreigners but 
police and security officials kept the group under tight control 
this is my brother mrs gordon 53 told the kazakhs 
crowded around her photographs he was watching our sheep when 
the cloud of radiation came over in 1954 he got burns on his arms 
and his hair fell out the sheep died his horse died 
four years later her teenage brother had cancer of the 
pancreas he died after four years mrs gordon said the kazakhs 
told stories of relatives crippled retarded or sickly 
in the 1950s historian amantai isin recalled his family lived 
in a village within the boundaries of the test site officials 
would take them away during a blast but bring them back home the 
same day no one ever suggested not drinking the milk from the 
family cows 
after one great blast in 1954 isins 5yearold brother came 
down with a terrible headache and died his father and another 
brother both died in their 30s he said isin is 39 
the activists traded grisly statistics 
mrs gordon said 13 of 17 children born in one year in the 1950s 
in cedar city utah had birth defects 
dr mayra zhangelova director of the semipalatinsk medical 
institute said birth defects per 10000 births in the soviet areas 
nearly tripled from 118 in 1980 to 292 in 1985 
foreign scientists in the group said the evidence of correlation 
to nuclear testing is strong but cannot be proved because of the 
time lag 
mrs gordon pulled out another photo showing a plume pouring 
from the earth in 1970 the kazakhs were shocked this was long 
after both the united states and the soviet union agreed to keep 
all blasts underground 
it was an accident she explained but accidents can 
happen 
we also fear this the crowd chimed in 
do you think there will be action on this at the summit 
asked one kazakh woman referring to wednesdays meeting between 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev and president bush in 
washington 
mrs gordon replied that a us ambassador had told her no 
she said she infuriated the official by calling for nuclear tests 
underneath the pentagon 
thats great beamed a kazakh woman reaching out to shake 
her hand 
</TEXT>
