<TEXT>
the united states and the soviet union enter 
this weeks summit with renewed momentum toward clinching a treaty 
that for the first time would require each side to reduce the 
number of longrange nuclear weapons 
while a treaty wont be ready for formal agreement when 
president bush begins four days of meetings with soviet president 
mikhail s gorbachev on thursday the two men are expected to issue 
a joint statement this weekend declaring the main provisions of the 
pact to be settled the details on the other hand could be months 
away 
bush and gorbachev are expected to agree to drastically reduce 
their stockpiles of chemical weapons and to end production of those 
weapons in addition they are expected to call for ratification of 
two existing pacts limiting nuclear tests us and soviet 
officials met during the weekend in an effort to settle arms 
control issues 
the administration has said bush also will press gorbachev for a 
commitment to speed up natowarsaw pact negotiations to reduce 
tanks troops and other conventional armaments in europe progress 
in these talks has slowed recently 
these will be the main arms control features of the summit 
which comes almost exactly eight years after us and soviet 
negotiators met in geneva to begin the strategic arms reduction 
talks 
yet to be settled before a start treaty can be formally signed 
are anticheating provisions and the question of whether to limit 
mobile landbased missiles such as the soviet ss24 and the 
proposed american midgetman plus a number of other relatively 
minor points of disagreement 
aides to bush and gorbachev are set to work throughout the 
summit on disputed start issues and negotiating teams in geneva 
plan to press ahead this summer in hopes of pulling the final 
pieces together in time for a yearend summit signing ceremony 
analysts say the chances of success are high 
bush and gorbachev are expected to announce an agreement 
probably not in the form of a treaty to destroy all but 5000 tons 
of each sides chemical weapons arsenal this would be intended as 
a catalyst for concluding a global ban on chemical arms in the 
conference on disarmament in geneva terms for ensuring compliance 
with the ussoviet deal have yet to be settled 
the summit also is to declare the two sides agreement on a 
ussoviet protocol for verifying compliance with 1974 and 1976 
treaties that limit the size of underground nuclear tests bush and 
gorbachev are expected to say the agreement will permit both sides 
to push for legislative ratification of the treaties 
the proposed start treaty if completed and ratified would 
represent an important step in disarmament it would require about 
a onethird reduction in numbers of longrange nuclear weapons and 
also may lead to followup negotiations to cut strategic nuclear 
forces even further 
previous treaties on strategic arms including the unratified 
1979 salt ii accord limited the growth of longrange weaponry but 
did not actually reduce their numbers 
the proposed new treaty would reduce the combined us and 
soviet strategic nuclear warhead totals from about 23500 now to 
about 16000 by the late 1990s 
start makes good sense for the united states secretary of 
state james a baker iii told reporters last week in defending the 
administrations negotiating record 
yet the proposed accord is being attacked by critics at both 
ends of the us political spectrum conservatives say it concedes 
too much to the soviets while liberals say it doesnt go far enough 
in forcing a shift away from nuclear confrontation 
baker has come under heavy attack for dropping a longstanding 
us demand that the start treaty prohibit all soviet upgrading of 
its ss18 landbased intercontinental ballistic missile the 
backbone of the soviet strategic arsenal 
its a travesty said frank j gaffney jr director of the 
center for security policy a washington think tank he contends 
that ss18 qualitative improvements that may be permitted under 
start would offset the effects of moscows agreement to reduce the 
number of ss18s by 50 percent over a sevenyear period 
the treaty as now drafted would not require such drastic 
reductions in any element of the us strategic arsenal the 
proposed cut in us ballistic missiles would be about 35 percent 
while the total number of warheads for strategic forces including 
bombers and seabased weapons would be 25 percent according to 
stan norris of the private natural resources defense council 
norris sees only limited value in the treaty he argues that it 
would merely codify arms cuts that both superpowers were planning 
anyway because of budget pressures and aging systems 
as with many past treaties this will be arms control without 
pain or sacrifice he said 
the actual size of the reductions is difficult to calculate 
because no one is sure what political and financial forces will 
bear on each countrys military between now and the end of the 
treatys proposed sevenyear implementation period its unclear 
for example how many more of the new b2 stealth bombers the 
pentagon will buy at the going rate of 815 million each 
jack mendelsohn deputy director of the private arms control 
association and a former member of the us delegation to the salt 
ii and start negotiations calculates that the cut in american 
strategic nuclear warheads may be as little as 6 percent he 
figures the soviet reduction may be less than 15 percent 
</TEXT>
