<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to let states 
require stockbrokers to give investors the option of suing rather 
than seeking arbitration over alleged broker fraud 
the justices without comment let stand a ruling that barred 
massachusetts from requiring brokers to make arbitration clauses 
optional not mandatory in brokerage contracts 
the massachusetts appeal the court acted on today was supported 
by 30 other states whose officials said a federal appeals court 
ruling leaves them powerless to protect consumers from being 
coerced to enter arbitration agreements 
but the bush administration told the justices the massachusetts 
appeal should be rejected 
the 1st us circuit court of appeals in boston ruled aug 31 
that the massachusetts regulations are preempted by federal law 
the brokerage industry customarily requires customers to agree 
to arbitrate all disputes as a condition of opening an account 
but in 1987 the justices ruled by a 54 vote that if such 
arbitration clauses are in the contracts signed by investors 
disputes over alleged fraud are to be resolved in arbitration not 
in lawsuits 
massachusetts secretary of state in 1988 imposed regulations 
prohibiting brokers from making arbitration agreements 
nonnegotiable conditions for opening accounts the regulations 
also required brokers to tell customers about the legal effects of 
mandatory arbitration clauses 
the states action immediately was challenged by the securities 
industry association and 10 brokerage firms affiliated with it 
a federal judge ruled for the brokers and the appeals court 
upheld that ruling 
the long and short of it is that we can find no evidence of a 
clear congressional command to override the unambiguous 
proarbitration mandate of the federal arbitration act in the 
securities field the appeals court said 
in the states appeal massachusetts attorney general james m 
shannon said the august ruling has national implications for 
state regulation of mandatory arbitration agreements in banking 
health care the automobile and many other industries 
shannon said the federal arbitration act does not preempt all 
state regulation of arbitration 
lawyers for the securities industry and the justice department 
urged the justices to reject the states appeal government lawyers 
said federal law does preempt such state regulation 
the case is connolly vs securities industry association 89894 
</TEXT>
