<TEXT>
the supreme court today increased the federal 
governments power to keep some criminal defendants behind bars 
while they await trial even if a key bail law was violated 
the justices by a 63 vote spared the government from having 
to free on bail some defendants deemed to be dangerous or a risk to 
flee before trial 
the decision reversed a federal appeals court ruling that said 
pretrial release is required even for a defendant who could have 
been held in custody if a pretrial detention hearing is not held 
the first time that person appears in court 
the safety of society does not become forfeit to the accident 
of the noncompliance with statutory time limits where the 
government is ready and able to show release on bail is not 
feasible justice anthony m kennedy wrote for the court 
neither the timing requirements nor any other part of the 
bail reform act of 1984 can be read to require or even suggest 
that a timing error must result in the release of a person who 
should otherwise be detained kennedy said 
justices john paul stevens william j brennan and thurgood 
marshall dissented 
writing for the three stevens said that in writing the bail law 
congress required prosecutors to turn square corners 
the court today however permits federal prosecutors to 
violate the law with impunity 
the justices in 1987 upheld the federal law allowing denial of 
bail before trial to people deemed dangerous to the community even 
if accused of nonviolent crimes 
before the 1984 law pretrial bail generally would be denied 
only if a judge determined the defendant was likely to flee 
in practice however federal judges could get around the old 
law by setting very high bail ostensibly aimed at guaranteeing the 
defendants appearance in court but effectively keeping the accused 
in custody while awaiting trial 
a provision in the 1984 law states that a hearing to determine 
whether pretrial detention is justified must be held immediately 
upon the persons first appearance before the judicial officer 
unless that person or the attorney for the government seeks a 
continuance 
a federal trial judge and the 10th us circuit court of appeals 
ruled that the first appearance provision of the law had been 
ignored in the case of guadalupe montalvomurillo charged with 
possessing nearly 1 million worth of cocaine 
montalvomurillo a mexican legally living in this country was 
stopped in february 1989 while driving a pickup truck near the 
mexican border at orogrande nm 
us customs service agents found 72 pounds of cocaine with a 
wholesale value of almost 1 million in the truck 
at a feb 16 1989 proceeding a federal magistrate put off a 
detention hearing until feb 21 after that hearing the magistrate 
decided to release montalvomurillo on 50000 bail 
government prosecutors appealed to a federal judge who ruled 
that montalvomurillo posed both a danger to the community and a 
risk to flee 
but the judge ruled that the new mexico magistrate in 
postponing the detention hearing for five days violated the 
federal bail laws first appearance rule the judge said the 
only appropriate remedy was the defendants release on bail 
montalvomurillo was freed on 88500 bail and has been a 
fugitive from justice ever since he is believed to have fled to 
mexico 
the case is us vs montalvomurillo 89163 
</TEXT>
