a luxury liner was refloated from a delaware 
bay sand bar today and headed for port after passengers were 
ferried ashore ending nearly two days of merrymaking 
the estimated 1000 passengers on the 642foot regent star were 
treated to free food and drinks sang christmas carols and played 
the newlywed game 
i had a beautiful time said mary poniatowsky 66 a 
baltimore bar owner a lot of people were partying but i didnt 
because im not a drinker 
it wasnt a bad party said a woman passenger who was met by 
friends and family at dockside 
the ship had been headed for philadelphia on the final leg of a 
sevenday cruise from jamaica when a small fire early sunday 
knocked out power and allowed the vessel to run onto a sand bar a 
mile off fortescue nj 
aboard were 1360 people including about 300 crew members 
nobody was in danger during the two days aground the coast guard 
said 
efforts to push the ship free with tugboats were halted for fear 
the vessel would spill fuel and the passengers were transferred to 
a ferry that normally runs between lewes and cape may nj 
the cheering passengers were put ashore monday night 100 miles 
short of their destination and got on buses to be taken to their 
cars at airports and bus stations in the philadelphia 
baltimorewashington and new york city areas 
the ship was finally refloated at high tide with help from 
tugboats early today and initially was moved to an anchorage off 
slaughter beach del according to the coast guard 
coast guard lt james weakley said officials have not seen any 
evidence of pollution divers were supposed to check the hull of 
the ship today for leaks or other damage but he said that plan was 
scrapped because of the weather and a decision was made to take the 
ship into philadelphia 
when the lights went out in the disco passenger kathleen 
hopkins said everybody was singing hot hot hot later they 
sang christmas carols and played an improvised version of the 
newlywed game she said 
people started chanting drinks drinks drinks and free 
mimosas started flowing hopkins said 
another passenger barbara sowden of wilmington del said by 
phone it just gave us a great opportunity to party hardy a 
little longer we dont need a band we make our own music 
ann burguieres a spokeswoman for regency cruises said 
theyre always well stocked there is always plenty of food and 
drink on a cruise 
ms poniatowsky and dorothy klausmeyer 63 a store clerk in the 
baltimore area were the first two passengers off the ferry 
what could you do we slept we took pictures said ms 
poniatowsky 
ms klausmeyer said she heard a thud early sunday morning when 
the ship ran aground and i started to yell i didnt know what was 
happening then they explained it to us and we were all ok 
