<TEXT>
the justice department today asked the 
independent counsel investigating former housing secretary samuel 
r pierce jr to investigate fresh allegations of political 
favoritism at the agency 
attorney general dick thornburgh made the request in a may 25 
letter to independent counsel arlin m adams a copy of the letter 
was released today by the justice department after it was received 
by adams 
in his letter thornburgh asked the courtappointed independent 
counsel to review allegations of favoritism in the operation of the 
department of housing and urban developments urban development 
action grant program and the secretarys discretionary fund for 
technical assistance and special projects 
the request for adams to broaden his inquiry was based on a 
review of testimony recently given to a house subcommittee by 
dubois gilliam former deputy assistant hud secretary for program 
policy development and evaluation according to the letter 
gilliam who is serving an 18month sentence for conspiracy and 
accepting illegal gratuities told a house subcommittee that pierce 
told him on several occasions to award hud grants to projects that 
were supported by influential republicans 
gilliam who operated the udag program said pierce ordered him 
to ordered to approve a 23 million grant for an apartment complex 
and shopping center on land owned by hampton university where 
pierce was a trustee 
gilliam told the house government operations subcommittee in 
testimony earlier this month that pierce told him to intervene in 
projects in cleveland miami and nashville 
justice department spokesman daniel eramian said gilliams 
testimony about the operation of hud during the reagan 
administration was reviewed by prosecutors in the criminal division 
in his letter to adams thornburgh said gilliams allegations 
concerning how the funding decisions in these programs were made 
are related to the allegations you are already investigating 
concerning huds moderate rehabilitation program 
adams said in a statement that it would appear that in light 
of gilliams testimony it may be appropriate to redefine the 
mandate of the independent counsel 
i shall of course carefully consider this letter from the 
attorney general during the next few days and take action 
promptly said adams who noted he received the letter today 
adams was appointed by a special court earlier this year to 
investigate allegations that pierce and top aides defrauded the 
government by awarding moderate rehabilitation program grants on 
the basis of political favoritism between 1984 and 1988 
the narrow jurisdiction was sought by thornburgh following 
hearings last year by the same house subcommittee chaired by rep 
thomas lantos dcalif 
democrats in congress have repeatedly asked thornburgh to expand 
the scope of adamss jurisdiction 
gilliams testimony given under a grant of limited immunity 
from prosecution conflicts with pierces sworn assertions to the 
subcommittee that he never ordered aides to approve specific grants 
</TEXT>
