<TEXT>
candidates supported by the solidarity 
trade union held a strong lead over the communists in community 
council elections across the nation according to unofficial 
returns reported today 
preliminary results from the national general election 
commission indicated that solidarity candidates swept 59 of 60 
seats in the baltic port of gdansk where the union was founded 
nearly a decade ago 
candidates backed by the union also were reported to be doing 
well in the large cities of warsaw krakow katowice and 
czestochowa in the first free elections for local councils since 
world war ii 
there were 52000 individual races for seats on more than 2000 
councils and the official results were to be announced wednesday 
during four decades of communist rule polands ommunity 
councils were largely under the control of the central government 
in warsaw but the new ones will be autonomous 
despite strong campaign efforts the reformed communist party 
appeared to have done poorly 
the social democrats as the former communists call themselves 
won two seats in the cities of kielce and czestochowa four in 
opole six in lodz and 15 out of 341 seats in warsaw according to 
the unofficial returns 
voter turnout was only 42 percent and it appeared many people 
stayed away because of confusion over the large number of parties 
running candidates 
nearly 80 new parties have been formed in the last six months 
but many have not presented clearly defined programs 
the most organized political force in the country is the local 
citizens committees founded a year ago by solidarity supporters to 
contest elections 
they faced competition in some areas 
a group representing ethnic byelorussians won a majority of the 
vote in the town of bialowieza and about 25 percent of the vote in 
two other towns in the northeastern province of bialystok not far 
from the soviet border 
the confederation for an independent poland a small 
anticommunist group that has been politically active for a decade 
won three council seats in the city of lublin one in katowice and 
12 in lodz but leszek moczulski the leader of the group lost his 
race in warsaw 
residents of gdansk province also voted on a referendum on the 
construction of a nuclear power plant in zarnowiec the pap news 
agency reported today it said 80 percent of the voters were 
against the project 
