<TEXT>
an ancient murrelet is drawing hundreds 
of birdwatchers to the bristol channel in southwest england far 
from its normal habitat 
this bird has never been recorded outside the northern pacific 
ocean before and its appearance in britain is likely to be the 
bird sighting of 1990 richard millington who runs an 
information service on rare bird visitors said tuesday 
the visitor was first sighted in jennys cove on lundy island in 
the bristol channel 
millingtons telephone service birdline provided details of 
boats for hire in the north devon coastal town of bideford to ferry 
birdwatchers out to the island one boat alone was hired to take 
250 people to the scene 
the ancient murrelet is a small member of the auk family of 
diving birds its main breeding grounds are on the aleutians and 
other islands off western alaska in winter it flies south as far 
as korea 
