facility would overcome one obstacle in the way of the strategic 
arms treaty both the reagan and now the bush administrations have 
said they would not sign a strategic arms reduction treaty until 
the giant radar facility is dismantled 
we recently saw signs that this is going on said one 
official who spoke on condition of anonymity 
the reagan administration had contended the installation 
violated the 1972 antiballistic missile treaty which imposes 
strict limits on radar after protesting initially the soviets 
eventually relented and said they would dismantle the facility 
the two countries arms control negotiating teams met in three 
sessions sunday totaling 6 hours and then for 2 hours on monday 
the us delegation was headed by undersecretary reginald 
bartholomew and the soviet group by deputy prime minister viktor p 
karpov an experienced arms control negotiator 
