<TEXT>
soviet pollution is choking finnish 
lapland threatening what is considered europes last wilderness 
scientists say 
some experts predict ecological death for the pristine pine 
forests and arctic tundra in a decade unless quick action is taken 
we are used to drinking water from the lakes and streams in 
lapland but if the pollution continues at current levels i give 
the region 10 years said satu huttunen professor of botany at 
the university of oulu in north finland 
finnish lapland makes up about a third of the country and is 
largely uninhabited by humans home to bears wolves moose and 
other animals it also provides a recreation area for skiers and 
canoeists 
finnish officials say the problem begins with large soviet 
nickel and apatite plants in the kola peninsula that spew out 
770000 tons of sulphur dioxide into the atmosphere each year 
most of it falls into soviet territory but foresters in 
northeast finland have reported increasing levels of pollutants 
some of the sulphur concentrations are three times higher than 
the vulnerable arctic nature can tolerate in fact concentrations 
in some finnish cities are lower than in the isolated corner of 
lapland mrs huttunen told the associated press 
last week prime minister harri holkeri visited the soviet 
industries in the region with soviet deputy prime minister stepan 
sitaryan 
