<TEXT>
two senate committee chairmen on tuesday 
proposed revamping us foreign aid to make it more supportive of 
american business interests overseas 
sens david boren dokla and lloyd bentsen dtexas said a 
larger portion of us economic aid should be tied to purchases of 
american goods and services they proposed legislation to boost the 
figure from the current 7 percent to 40 percent by 1996 
competitors such as japan west germany and france already make 
heavy use of such tied aid they said 
more and more we have come to understand that competition in 
the world today is primarily economic rather than military boren 
said at a news conference he said polls show americans are 
increasingly disenchanted with foreign aid spending 
boren chairman of the intelligence committee said he and 
finance committee chairman bentsen were being joined in the effort 
by sen robert byrd dwva chairman of the appropriations 
committee 
their suggestion is likely to join various ideas for revamping 
foreign aid as congress seeks to adapt a decadesold aid system to 
the new realities of eastern european democracies and collapsing 
centrally planned economies 
many of the ideas reflect a need for aid to be aimed less at 
military security for friendly nations as it has been through the 
cold war era and more at economic warfare 
boren called it a tragic waste that the united states gave 
most of its recent 800 million in aid to poland in cash with no 
strings attached while west germany and japan gave nearly 3 
billion that could be spent only to buy goods from those countries 
i think it is time we adjust to what our economic competitors 
are doing boren said we should offer american goods when 
developing nations are cleaning up their environment and building 
their infrastructure transportation systems communications 
networks and new plants with new technologies 
boren proposed as a safeguard that the shift of aid money not 
penalize the poorest countries particularly those in africa which 
now receive direct grants for programs like public health 
population control and agricultural development 
the proposal also included a 15 percent increase in the ceiling 
for direct loans by the exportimport bank to finance purchases of 
us goods by overseas buyers increases in other credit programs 
tied to purchase of american products and a new 1 billion loan 
guarantee program for eastern europe to encourage an aggressive 
us presence in that new market 
</TEXT>
