<TEXT>
the supreme court today effectively extended 
the long arm of the law in the case of a couple who split up and 
now live on opposite coasts 
the justices voting 90 said new jersey resident dennis 
burnham must answer to courts in california in a divorce suit by 
his wife francie burnham 
the court ruled that someone who visits a state may be sued 
there by a state resident even if the visitor has only minimal 
contacts with that state the ruling is likely to have significant 
impact in other divorce and custody cases 
burnham was greeted by a process server in january 1988 when he 
went to california to spend some time with the couples children 
who live with their mother in the san francisco area 
the supreme court said today that burnhams presence in 
california although brief was enough for the california courts to 
have authority over him in the divorce proceeding 
justice antonin scalia in the courts main opinion said 
burnhams due process rights are not violated by forcing him to 
contest his wifes divorce claim in california 
jurisdiction based on physical presence alone constitutes due 
process because it is one of the continuing traditions of our legal 
system that define notions of fair play and substantial 
justice he said 
joining his opinion were chief justice william h rehnquist and 
justices byron r white and anthony m kennedy 
the other five justices agreed that burnhams rights were not 
violated but in separate concurring opinions declined to go along 
with scalias reasoning they supported a casebycase approach 
precluded by scalias broader pronouncement 
the burnhams were married in 1976 and lived in new jersey until 
they separated in july 1987 when mrs burnham took their two 
children to california 
burnham sued for divorce in 1987 in new jersey accusing his 
wife of desertion she said the suit violated their agreement that 
they were splitting up over irreconciliable differences 
when burnham visited his family in january 1988 he took one of 
the children on an outing to san francisco when he returned to his 
wifes home in nearby mill valley he was served with a summons and 
a copy of her divorce petition 
the california courts denied his motion to quash the service of 
process rejecting arguments that he only had minimum contacts with 
the state 
court papers did not specify where burnham lives in new jersey 
the case is burnham vs superior court of california 8944 
