<TEXT>
burmas first competitive election in 30 
years may have given this impoverished nation a chance to start 
anew in building a democratic government 
but skepticism and anxieties persist about how the powerful 
military which has held authoritarian power since 1962 will react 
to the turn of events 
to the surprise of many analysts the countrys leading 
opposition party the national league for democracy appears to 
have scored a huge victory over conservative promilitary forces 
final results from sundays general election may not be in for 
weeks but in votecounting through tuesday the party backed by 
the military had yet to win a single seat in the 492seat 
parliament 
the national league for democracy had won 41 of the 43 
parliamentary seats decided and said it was certain it would hold 
at least 322 seats when counting was finished 
the mood in this city of crumbling british colonialera 
buildings has changed dramatically since the vote 
saturday people dared not take the leaflets i was handing out 
now they talk freely said a party organizer tuesday 
but the future appears unclear the military has promised to 
turn over power after the new parliament writes a constitution and 
a strong civilian government is in place there is no indication 
when this will be achieved 
its still a very murky situation it has never happened 
before and i think the army is still scratching its head and 
wondering how to handle it said one senior western diplomat 
if you look back in history the armys attitude is not firm 
they often change their color do you see the point said an 
official of the national league for democracy who requested 
anonymity 
it was the army that killed several thousand mostly unarmed 
civilians when the country rose up against authoritarian rule in 
1988 
a group of military leaders led by gen saw maung crushed the 
uprising in september 1988 imposed martial law and carried out 
widespread arrests it did call for general elections and for a 
time allowed relatively free political activity 
but when opposition leader aung san suu kyi the charismatic 
daughter of independence hero aung san criticized the military and 
gathered mass support last summer she was put under house arrest 
the coleader of the national league for democracy tin oo was 
also jailed former prime minster nu also remains under house 
arrest 
other political prisoners remain in detention and arrests 
continued until just before the election five days before 
balloting zagana a popular comedian who took part in the 1988 
uprising was sentenced to five years in prison by a military 
tribunal 
given this prelude diplomats human rights organizations and 
others branded the elections fraudulent yet from all available 
accounts including observation by foreign correspondents the 
balloting was free and fair 
the united states praised the burmese for the election and said 
tuesday that from the early results it is apparent the burmese 
people want to return to a multiparty political system 
some analysts speculate that the military miscalculated the 
burmese peoples dissatisfaction with their situation 
they simply did not realize how deeply unpopular the 
promilitary national unity party and by extension they 
themselves were said a rangoonbased western diplomat 
the opposition is taking the election at face value the 
military called an election prodemocracy forces won and now have 
a mandate from the people 
people who until recently did not dare approach foreigners in 
public are speaking freely although they do not always want their 
names printed 
im very happy to see fresh new faces in parliament and im 
glad to see those old cronies who had devastated the economy leave 
the scene said one retired civil servant this election has 
turned a page in burmese history 
this is not the first effort at democracy in modern burmese 
history after independence from great britain in 1962 a 
parliamentary democracy was established 
it scored some successes but factionalism rebellions by ethnic 
groups and other problems plagued the fledgling experiment the 
army stepped in on several occasions and finally seized power in a 
1962 coup led by gen ne win 
ne win and his oneparty state led the country to economic ruin 
isolationism and political stagnation 
ne win retired in 1988 and some say his withdrawal from the 
political arena contributed to the election triumph of the league 
for democracy others believe he is still pulling strings behind 
the scene 
