<TEXT>
in a decision that will severely restrict 
assistance to 15 million refugees worldwide the united nations 
high commissioner for refugees agreed tuesday to a sharp cut in its 
1990 budget 
the agencys executive committee agreed that expenditure on 
general programs should be limited to 341 million in 1990 in order 
to tackle a financial crisis overwhelming the organization 
in a speech on the opening day of the emergency meeting monday 
deputy high commissioner douglas stafford said a deficit of 82 
million was forecast for 1990 he said overall spending needs were 
estimated at 672 million 
last years general budget was 389 million and in october the 
executive committee proposed a 414 million budget for 1990 
high commissioner thorvald stoltenberg said in an 11page report 
to the meeting that the revised budget was a reasonable balance 
between the needs of refugees and income expected from donor 
governments 
he said said education and support programs were being slashed 
as a result of the financial crisis and that 10 percent to 15 
percent of the 2400 agency employees would be cut 
supplies of food clothing blankets and fuel are being cut to 
inadequate levels in many refugee camps while lack of resources 
for transport and road repairs is imposing further limits on 
supplies according to the report 
the report said refugee protection was also suffering it cited 
insufficient staff to monitor vietnamese boat people in southeast 
asian countries to separate genuine refugees fleeing political 
persecution from those escaping economic hardship 
stoltenberg said cuts in programs to repatriate refugees or 
integrate them into local economies meant people would have to 
remain in camps at great expense 
in 1980 unhcr had twice as many resources for each refugee 
than it has in 1990 stoltenberg said 
the meeting in geneva was held to fix spending for the rest of 
1990 and to make an initial assessment of needs in 1991 all agency 
money is based on voluntary contributions from governments 
