<TEXT>
new orleans and new york are the finalists in 
the competition to host the 1992 democratic national convention 
party sources said tuesday 
the 46member site selection committee will recommend the two 
cities wednesday to party chairman ronald h brown who will make 
the final decision the sources said 
the convention is scheduled to open july 13 1992 and run for 
four days 
brown plans to visit both cities possibly as early as next 
week and announce his decision in midjune 
the 1988 democratic convention was held in atlanta 
new york was the site of the 1976 convention when the democrats 
nominated jimmy carter for president the last time the party won a 
national election 
new orleans hosted the 1988 republican convention that nominated 
george bush 
in addition to the two finalists the site selection committee 
also considered bids from cleveland and houston 
while cleveland impressed committee members with its 
enthusiastic presentation the city was unable to overcome its 
shortage of hotel space the city planned to house some convention 
participants on boats docked on lake erie 
the democrats insisted on access to the hall for six weeks prior 
to the opening of the convention and also asked for a commitment of 
15 million in support services to include police protection and 
rental of the facility 
those two requirements proved too much for several cities that 
were invited to bid but later declined to enter the competition 
the convention is expected to attract 35000 people to the host 
city and millions of dollars in economic benefits atlanta was 
estimated to have gained about 70 million from the 1988 convention 
that nominated michael dukakis for president 
new york made the strongest financial bid of any city offering 
the democrats 22 million in upfront money and services but 
madison square garden was regarded as only marginally adequate for 
the convention city officials offered a plan to provide additional 
seating but several selection committee members were skeptical 
in addition the media workspace in new york would be in the 
javits center half a mile from the convention site 
new orleans had trouble meeting the financial requirement and is 
located in a state that is considered a stronghold of the 
antiabortion movement placing it at odds with the prevailing 
sentiment of the democratic party but its superdome offered more 
than enough space for the delegates plus the thousands of news 
media needing room to work 
both cities were able to guarantee plenty of hotel rooms and are 
home to some of the nations best known restaurants 
the republicans also have begun their site selection process and 
plan to announce the gop convention site in january 
