<TEXT>
the worlds newspapers trying to battle 
illiteracy and boost future readership by getting schoolchildren to 
read papers face growing competition from television international 
publishing spokesmen said tuesday 
even among young readers in japan with its low illiteracy 
rates disenchantment with newspapers is proceeding at a 
frightening pace said kazuo ichiriki owner of the newspaper 
kahoku shimpo in sendai 
japanese high school students spend an average of just six 
minutes a day reading newspapers and 20 percent of university 
students dont read newspapers daily ichiriki told participants at 
a international literacy conference sponsored by the american 
newspaper publishers association foundation 
the conference focused on anpas 25yearold newspapers in 
education program aimed at promoting use of newspapers in schools 
worldwide to help youngsters develop lifelong reading habits 
the international gathering which drew 165 participants from 20 
nations was a prelude to a threeday conference in new york 
beginning wednesday 
among the topics to be discussed later in the week classroom 
newscasts by cnn and channel one by whittle communications 
some publishers fear such programming could squeeze newspapers 
out of the curriculum 
we are in a war in fighting for resources and recognitiion in 
schools said uzal h martz jr president and publisher of the 
pottsville pa republican 
japanese publishers began an nie program 4 years ago said 
ichiriki because people from that nation were spending just 30 
minutes a day reading and two hours a day watching tv about 85 
percent of japanese schools now make use of newspapers in classroom 
lessons 
but nie is not just to protect our selfinterest as newspaper 
publishers but because the future of japan could be adversely 
affected he said 
representatives of several other foreign language newspapers 
published in the united states and abroad issued similar warnings 
that newspapers needed to make a more concerted effort to regain 
students attention in the face of growing competition from 
television 
in sweden newspaper readership among 9to14yearolds recently 
has declined after a decade of stability largely because of 
increased television viewing said birgitta pahlen newspapers in 
education manager for the swedish newspaper publishers association 
in stockholm 
in less developed countries poverty or indifference pose the 
larger threat to literacy efforts employing newspapers in india 
for example with 280 million illiterates only one nie effort 
exists according to john ryan coordinator for unescos 
international literacy year 
</TEXT>
