<TEXT>
more than half the states are responding to 
unexpectedly sharp increases in food prices by cutting back on a 
federally funded program that provides food for women infants and 
children authorities said tuesday 
it means we wont have as many healthy children and mothers as 
we wanted because all of these people are medically at risk for 
malnutrition and anemia rep tony p hall dohio said 
youve got to be in trouble to be in the program in the first 
place 
the changes are being made in the 21 billion special 
supplemental food program for women infants and children known as 
wic which in february provided groceries to an alltime high 455 
million individuals 
hall chairman of the house select hunger committee has been 
calling for a 150 million increase in the program for each of the 
next five years but he said that even with that money in 1991 if 
we stay even well be lucky 
the program provides needy women and children with vouchers 
redeemable at the grocery store for food including milk infant 
formula juice cheese and cereal 
price increases for milk and to a lesser degree orange juice and 
cereal have been named as the prime sources of the budgetary strain 
the department of agricultures food and nutrition service 
which runs the program had figured on inflation in food prices 
this year of a little more than 4 percent 
but the costs of food staples have risen about double that 
straining state programs 
dennis bach head of the iowa program and president of the 
national association of wic directors said 36 of the 44 states 
that responded to a recent survey said they were cutting benefits 
under the program hall said a hunger committee study found similar 
results 
only about half of those eligible are receiving benefits 
according to bach many states are not able to provide food to 
individuals who fall into the lowest priority categories 
there are literally millions of young children who would 
qualify for wic who are not getting served bach said 
weve talked to the states about the first measure being to 
find less expensive ways to provide the same nutrition without 
cutting volume of food or nutritional value of food said f 
philip shanholtzer a spokesman for the food and nutritional 
service 
texas has cut the cereal allowance for 1yearolds and 
2yearolds from 36 ounces a month to 24 ounces a month and will 
drop 27000 program participants those receiving benefits reached 
a peak of 357000 in january 
when prices go up on food items that means our budget wont 
go as far and we have to serve fewer people said ray krzesniak 
chief of staff services for the health departments bureau of 
women infants and children 
texas receives 148 million from usda under the program as well 
as 55 million in state funds plus a hefty rebate on each can of 
infant formula 
iowa which has a much smaller program is nonetheless planning 
to end benefits for postpartum women who are not breast feeding a 
low priority on the usda scale that would drop an estimated 4000 
participants and reduce the total of individuals receiving benefits 
to 45000 for a 400000 savings 
california which currently serves 470000 individuals is 
planning to cut the monthly juice allowance for children three to 
five years old for an expected savings of 12 million it also is 
hoping to save 6 million by eliminating vouchers for cheese 
</TEXT>
