<TEXT>
the justice department on tuesday asked the 
special prosecutor investigating former housing secretary samuel r 
pierce jr to study new allegations of favoritism toward 
politically connected developers 
attorney general dick thornburgh asked independent counsel arlin 
m adams to review allegations by one of pierces former top aides 
dubois l gilliam that politics was an important criteria for 
awarding grants through two additional programs operated by the 
department of housing and urban development 
adams who is already investigating whether pierce and top aides 
illegally dispensed political favors in managing the moderate 
rehabilitation program said he would act promptly on thornburghs 
request 
it would appear that in light of gilliams testimony it may 
be appropriate to redefine the mandate of the independent 
counsel adams said in a statement after the justice department 
released a copy of thornburghs letter 
thornburgh based his request on testimony that gilliam who is 
serving an 18month sentence for corruption gave a house 
subcommittee about the operation of the urban development action 
grant program and the secretarys discretionary fund for technical 
assistance and special projects 
mr gilliams allegations concerning how the funding decisions 
in these programs were made are related to the allegations you are 
already investigating concerning huds moderate rehabilitation 
program the attorney general said 
accordingly i consider it proper and appropriate to refer 
those allegations to you for investigation thornburgh wrote 
justice department spokesman dan eramian said thornburghs 
request for a wider investigation was based on a review of 
gilliams sworn testimony by criminal division prosecutors 
paul perito pierces attorney called gilliams testimony 
scurrilous allegations and denounced the congressional 
committee that called him as a witness 
pierce perito said has nothing to fear by an impartial 
review by a group of dedicated and responsible prosecutors as 
opposed to the hysteria and insatiable thirst for publicity of a 
congressional inquiry gone awry 
gilliam testified that during the reagan administration hud was 
the best domestic political machine id ever seen we dealt 
strictly with politics there 
if you were well connected in political circles your 
application got strong strong consideration said gilliam who 
was deputy assistant secretary for policy development and 
evaluation 
gilliams testimony given under a grant of limited immunity 
from prosecution contradicts pierces own sworn assertions to the 
same subcommittee last spring that he never ordered aides to 
approve particular grants 
i know for a fact the secretary made decisions on specific 
projects gilliam said during his congressional testimony earlier 
this month 
in one case gilliam said pierce ordered him to approve a 23 
million grant for an apartment complex and shopping center on land 
owned by hampton university where pierce was a trustee 
gilliam said that pierce ordered the approval of a 56 million 
udag grant to a project in florida because his former executive 
assistance lance h wilson was a private consultant for the 
developer 
gilliam told the subcommittee that pierce ordered him to 
intervene in projects in nashville cleveland and miami that were 
supported by influential local republicans 
adams was appointed by a special court earlier this year to 
investigate allegations that pierce and top aides defrauded the 
government by awarding moderate rehabilitation program grants on 
the basis of political favoritism from 1984 to 1988 
the special prosecutor law allows adams to accept a broader 
jurisdiction at the request of the attorney general 
the original jurisdiction was defined by thornburgh in his 
request to the special court for the appointment of adams 
democrats on capitol hill have repeatedly called for a wider scope 
of the independent counsels inquiry 
gilliam who told lawmakers he took 100000 in bribes and 
gratuities while working at hud from 1984 to 1987 pleaded guilty 
last year to conspiring to manipulate the award of a grant and 
accepting 8000 in illegal gratuities 
rep charles schumer dny one of several house judiciary 
committee members who spearheaded the call for an independent 
counsel last fall welcomed the move but called for even wider 
jurisdiction 
i still do not understand however why perjury is not 
included in the independent counsels jurisdiction it would be 
best if the attorney general issue a broad mandate and let the 
independent counsels investigation go where the evidence 
warrants schumer said in a statement 
thornburgh found there was insufficient basis to investigate 
pierce for allegedly lying to the subcommittee saying the former 
secretary was asked ambiguous questions 
