<TEXT>
a judge refused tuesday to overturn john m 
poindexters five irancontra convictions ruling that the former 
national security adviser had presented a weak defense against 
strong evidence 
us district judge harold h greene denied defense motions for 
a judgment of acquittal on the five felony convictions of 
thenpresident reagans national security adviser 
a review of this evidence reveals that proof of defendants 
guilt of the charges is compelling greene said of the 
conspiracy obstruction of congress and false statement convictions 
that were returned april 7 by the jury in the case 
jurors found poindexter guilty of lying to congress and 
destroying documents to conceal covert reagan administration 
assistance of the nicaraguan rebels and the us role in a 1985 
israeli shipment of hawk missiles to iran 
the judge rejecting defense arguments that prosecutors did not 
prove their case against the retired navy rear admiral found that 
poindexters defense was neither broad nor particularly 
convincing 
other than to attempt to weaken the testimony of the 
governments witnesses through crossexamination poindexter simply 
did not have a defense of his own the judge said 
poindexter who did not testify at his trial is scheduled to be 
sentenced 
june 11 when he could be given up to 25 years in prison and 
fined as much as 125 million 
the judge noted that neither reagan who gave a videotaped 
deposition that was played to the jury nor former national 
security council aide oliver l north was willing to relieve 
defendant of culpability in their testimony 
the judge found that reagan may have helped generate an 
atmosphere at the white house which led subordinate officials to 
conclude they were carrying out the presidents wishes by 
repeatedly stressing his commitment to freeing us hostages in 
lebanon and helping the nicaraguan rebels after congress cut off 
aid 
but greene said there is no evidence to contradict the former 
presidents testimony that he warned his subordinates against 
acting outside the law 
the judge also dismissed a defense contention that irancontra 
prosecutor dan webb improperly argued to jurors in his final 
summation that reagan had lied to the american public when he 
denied selling arms to iran for hostages 
poindexters lawyers argued this was an improper expression of 
personal opinion not based on the facts 
while the language regarding a former president of the united 
states should perhaps have been more delicate the prosecutors 
assertion was nevertheless a fair inference from the evidence 
greene said 
