the state department said tuesday it has 
received numerous reports of torture by chinese authorities in 
tibet and it called on china to take effective measures to guard 
against such abuses 
state department spokeswoman margaret tutwiler said the reports 
received by us officials were similar to those contained in a 
study by asia watch a privatehuman rights group 
the report said the incidence of serious torture in tibet is 
at least as bad as it has been for years and in some cases worse 
some officials have suggested chinas decision to lift martial 
law in tibet a month ago was aimed at encouraging the bush 
administration not to revoke trade privileges for china 
ignoring appeals from some members of congress president bush 
announced last week that chinas mostfavorednation trade status 
would be retained 
about two weeks after martial law was lifted a us consular 
official visited tibet to review the human rights situation there 
it was the first visit of its kind since martial law was imposed 
and ms tutwiler expressed hope that such visits will be permitted 
in the future 
renewed diplomatic access will enable us to monitor the 
situation in tibet more directly and to raise human rights concerns 
with officials there she said 
the administration also hopes the lifting of martial law will 
lead to further easing of tensions and the release of those 
imprisoned for peaceful expression of political views she added 
the asia watch report said there is no indication that the 
lifting of martial law has led to the release of any political 
prisoners 
china regards tibet as an integral part of chinese territory but 
many tibetans favor independence 
