malaysia on wednesday hanged eight 
hong kong residents convicted of drug trafficking its highest 
number of executions in a single day prison officials said 
authorities rejected humanitarian appeals by british prime 
minister margaret thatcher and the human rights group amnesty 
international they also turned down new court efforts to block the 
killings of the eight convicted of smuggling 28 pounds of heroin 
despite widespread criticism malaysia has said it would 
continue a mandatory death penalty for anyone convicted of drug 
trafficking prime minister mahathir mohamad says illicit drug use 
is malaysias no 1 enemy with an estimated 350000 addicts 
among malaysias 178 million people 
since 1975 250 people have been sentenced to death for 
trafficking of those 92 have been hanged while the others are 
awaiting dates for hanging or appeals 
under malaysian law a drug trafficking conviction does not 
require proof of actual sale the possession of more than a 
halfounce of heroin or 3 ounces of marijuana is deemed to be 
trafficking 
two of the eight were hanged in kajang prison 18 miles south of 
kuala lumpur and the remainder in taiping prison 150 miles north 
of the capital 
among those killed was 32yearold waitress han tsui ling the 
first foreign woman to be hanged most of those executed were 
professionals from the british colony and they included a company 
supervisor and the director of an insurance company 
police said the eight were en route to brussels belgium with 
the heroin in five suitcases when they were arrested in october 
1982 at the penang international airport 180 miles northwest of 
kuala lumpur 
they were convicted in 1985 and the supreme court rejected 
their appeals last year 
wednesdays hanging of eight marked the highest number of people 
executed in malaysia on the same day prison officials said 
