yugoslavia soon will form a 
coalition government dominated by noncommunists prime minister 
ante markovic said in an interview published tuesday 
his comment was a significant step in efforts to resolve a 
political crisis that has paralyzed the country and eroded the 
fragile federation that unites its six ethnically and economically 
diverse republics 
the daily borba also quoted markovic as saying he might quit the 
communist party which has ruled yugoslavia since 1945 
markovic was named prime minister in march 1989 by the 
oneparty communist parliament but now hopes to keep his post in a 
free ballot his popularity has grown as his government has moved 
to halt fourdigit annual inflation and make the yugoslav currency 
the dinar convertible 
his suggestions of turning his government team into a separate 
party have drawn fierce criticism from hardline communists in 
serbia yugoslavias largest republic who fear losing their 
authority if markovic forms a new power base 
