edward louie creator of the fortune cookie 
folding machine and the popular risque fortune cookie has died at 
age 69 
louie returned from visiting his ancestral village in china two 
days before his death friday the trip fulfilled a promise made to 
his mother long ago the san francisco chronicle reported in 
tuesdays editions the cause of death was not immediately 
available 
louie gained notoriety after he invented a machine that 
automatically inserts the paper fortunes into the cookies as they 
are folded he created the device in an effort to save his family 
the labor of folding thousands of cookies by hand every day 
louie was best known however for two marketing ploys that were 
tremendously successful the giant fortune cookie and the risque 
cookie 
the giant fortune cookie was six inches wide and was sometimes 
filled with money or jewels the risque cookie of course 
contained suggestive fortunes and jokes 
louies parents farmers in a village near canton china 
emigrated to san francisco when louie was only 18 months old set 
on opening his own fortune cookie company louie opened the lotus 
fortune cookie co in 1946 
the entire louie clan worked at lotus flipping and folding the 
fortune cookies with chopsticks until he invented the folding 
machine in 1967 the original machine is still operating today 
contributing to the companys daily output of 90000 cookies 
to this day nothing breaks down said his son gregory 
louie 
