highway fatalities dropped last year after 
three straight years of increases from 47087 to 45454 and the 
nations top highway safety officer credits tighter laws 
advertising campaigns and greater public awareness 
the death toll represented the lowest ever in terms of miles 
traveled 
most of these regulations went in about two years ago but they 
really didnt take effect until last year jerry ralph curry the 
head of the national highway traffic safety administration said 
tuesday all of these things working together have dumped them 
down 
deaths involving passenger cars dropped from 25808 to 24929 in 
the united states last year as part of the overall decrease in 
highway fatalities the national transportation safety board 
reported highway fatalities account for 95 percent of all 
transportation deaths 
before all the figures were in the safety administration in 
february estimated 1989 fatalities at 45500 and said this figure 
was 22 deaths per 100 million miles traveled the smallest death 
rate on record the 1988 figure was 23 per 100 million miles and 
the 1980 rate was 33 per 100 million miles 
this was not an accident curry said we worked very hard 
along with the rest of the nation to make that happen 
he said seat belt use is up 
the leader of the nation is hawaii 78 percent belt use he 
said puerto rico is second with 70 percent new york state big 
as it is is next with 60 percent the national average seat belt 
use is 46 percent a total of 35 states now have seat belt laws 
he said 
curry also cited three million cars equipped with air bags now 
in use an ad campaign featuring two talking crash dummies and new 
state laws permitting administrative license suspensions for 
driving while drunk or drugged he said vermont connecticut 
maryland florida and california all passed such laws bringing the 
total number of states that have them to 29 
the number of people killed in alcohol and drugrelated 
accidents on the highway is still totally unacceptable said jim 
kolstad chairman of the ntsbalcohol and drug abuse continues to 
be one of the greatest threats to transportation safety facing our 
nation 
aviation deaths were practically unchanged 1160 in 1988 and 
1158 in 1989 general aviation deaths dropped from 796 to 763 and 
fatalities involving airlines from 285 to 277 but those decreases 
were offset by a rise in air taxi deaths from 58 to 86 and commuter 
airline deaths from 21 to 32 
