<TEXT>
crews scrambled tuesday to contain 
120000 gallons of fuel that spilled after an alaska railroad train 
derailed and scattered cars on both sides of the track 
seven of the 19 cars that derailed were leaking fuel railroad 
spokeswoman vivian hamilton said at the scene each of the tanker 
cars held 20000 gallons and two of them were totally drained 
a spokesman for the state department of environmental 
conservation earlier had erroneously said in juneau that all 19 
derailed cars were leaking 
the southbound train with 68 cars derailed at about 130 pm 
monday said arnold polanchek vice president of operations for the 
stateowned alaska railroad corp 
the fuel was en route to anchorage from the mapco alaska 
petroleum inc refinery in the town of north pole near fairbanks 
by early tuesday pumps and hoses had begun siphoning the fuel 
from the ground said paul bateman fairbanks program manager for 
the state environmental department 
weve got cars upside down sideways holed on both ends 
theyre in all shapes and condition its a mess said bateman 
who spent monday night at the scene 
railroad crews were also on the scene about 40 miles south of 
fairbanks near dunbar station polanchek said the crews worked to 
rebuild nearly 300 feet of track and remove the tanker cars they 
also laid absorbent boom and began trying to skim oil off the 
surface of a nearby creek 
no one was injured in the derailment and the company was trying 
to determine its cause polanchek said 
hundreds of tourists scheduled to visit denali national park and 
preserve and the mount mckinley area by train tuesday were to be 
bused around the wreck tour officials said 
the fuel had drained into two beaver ponds and into goldstream 
creek which flows into a wildlife refuge about 40 miles south of 
fairbanks it appeared to be at least several inches thick on a 
small stream that fed the creek 
more of the fuel probably would have run into the creek had it 
not been for some beaver dams that contained it a state 
environmental official said 
workers used a bulldozer to shore up one of the dams and used 
plywood and absorbent pads to strengthen the other said chuck 
kleeschulte of the state department of environmental conservation 
the beavers are very helpful he said 
railroad officials initially estimated the spills size at 
60000 to 80000 gallons but dale nelson an environmental 
engineer for the railroad later revised the estimate upward to 
120000 gallons of jet and diesel fuel 
this is a major spill one of the most major ive seen at the 
railroad nelson said 
the alaska railroad was purchased by the state from the federal 
government in 1985 it runs one freight train northbound and one 
train southbound daily 
