<DOCNO> AP900529-0187 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a halfdozen accordions stand on lawrence 
shine moutons kitchen table the result of hundreds of hours 
of work and decades of experience 
my daddy was a musician amadia breaux he composed jolie 
blonde i tried to learn to play but didnt learn to play as 
well as he did said mouton 63 i said if i couldnt play id 
learn to make em 
moutons name is now as well known among cajun musicians as his 
stepfathers his accordions are played by such performers as the 
popular zydecajun musician wayne toups and jimmy basile of 
cajun tradition the mamou group nominated for a grammy award this 
year 
as cajun music and its spinoffs have become more popular so has 
moutons craft about 45 people now make the little germanstyle 
squeeze boxes most of them in little backyard sheds 
i figured i wasnt any dumber than the next fellow i figured 
if he could make it i could make it too said john elton doucet 
whose workshop is in his grocery store the first one wasnt too 
too good but then the second one was good 
doucet makes six to 10 accordions a year its painstaking work 
the flat metal reeds and the bellows are imported from italy but 
everything else is made by hand 
or at least adapted for instance many people make the big 
silver buttons on the left end of the accordion from chromeplated 
chair glides they snip off the little prongs solder a wood screw 
onto the back and fill in the curve with lead 
you drill a hole and its all threaded and ready to go 
said larry miller who makes accordions only for his family but 
makes and sells cajun triangles spoons set in wooden blocks so 
theyre easy to use as a rhythm instrument and the 
overtheshoulder style metal washboards used by zydeco bands 
the four wooden stops used to close off the four sets of 
accordion reeds are made from cabinetwork spindles and tiny coiled 
screws inside the accordion were made to put tension on stereo 
tuning knobs 
some people paint their accordions others varnish them to show 
off finegrained woods the long curved halfdowels which open or 
close the reeds often are covered with gold mylar tape which gives 
even more glitter than the once traditional gold paint and is a lot 
easier to apply 
miller said he began learning to play the accordion because of a 
lecture from cajun music great dewey balfa after an assembly at 
the school where miller was principal miller told balfa that his 
father had made triangles and played accordion but none of his 
brothers or he had kept it up 
he said if youre concerned about it dying in your family 
itll probably be your fault you were the one that broke the 
chain recounted miller it hit me like a ton of bricks three 
days later i went and bought an accordion and commenced to 
learning 
about seven years later he started thinking about making the 
instruments he was influenced by stories he had heard about mouton 
and a few other men who had loved the instrument so much that 
after repairing and rerepairing german instruments made before 
world war ii they started making their own 
strictly speaking the cajun accordion is a melodeon or diatonic 
accordion a very different instrument from the big piano 
accordion popular shortly after the turn of the century 
for one thing the cajun accordion is much smaller its about 
11 inches high and six inches deep and will squeeze down to 14 
inches across it weighs about eight pounds less than a third the 
weight of its big cousin 
its held on with a strap around the back of the left hand and a 
smaller strap for the righthand thumb and played like a 
handdriven harmonica each of the 10 righthand buttons gives two 
notes one when the accordion is squeezed the other when its 
pulled out 
the 28pound piano accordion cant be held up without heavy 
padded shoulder straps its twooctave keyboard is twice as long as 
the cajun accordions little row of buttons each key always plays 
the same note 
since it does have all 12 notes of the chromatic scale it can 
play in any while the cajun accordion is limited to four if a 
player is particularly adept and plays every note of the scale 
only in one 
however cajun accordion makers say that their instrument can 
overpower the bigger one because it has four sets of melody reeds 
german accordions began showing up in cajun country around the 
1890s and quickly upstaged the quieter fiddle as lead instrument 
world war ii stopped imports and the factories were destroyed or 
converted to other uses 
factories resumed making accordions later but the style popular 
in louisiana four sets of reeds controlled by one set of buttons 
wasnt used much elsehwere 
mouton charlie ortego and sidney brown and marc savoy are 
generally considered the pioneers of modernday accordion building 
mouton began making accordions in 1961 opening up his fathers 
old germanmade sterling accordion and using it as a reference 
in 1970 heart trouble forced him to choose between a transfer 
and retirement from work as a civil engineer for conoco his hobby 
became his fulltime job 
not to say a living i dont make that much money making 
accordions because the cost of reeds and bellows is so high he 
said 
those two parts are ordered from italy and cost hundreds of 
dollars reed makers dont give any discounts miller said but he 
and about 25 other accordion makers recently began ordering bellows 
together 
i remember when you could buy reeds for 5 a set said 
mouton now the cheapest reeds are 90 and bellows start at 150 
and those are for a brand scorned as vastly inferior to those 
made in italy 
importing presents other problems i ordered some reeds oct 
19 1989 they have my money i still dont have the reeds said 
mouton 
mouton still works in a little backyard shed though his heart 
problems have cut back to six or seven hours a day and about 20 
accordions a year a friend has begun cutting out the wooden parts 
for him to put together 
photographs of his father and his wife betty stand on a shelf 
over his workbench on the walls are a plaque naming breaux to the 
cajun musicians hall of fame in 1984 musicians signed promotion 
photographs and several wayne toups posters one of them 
inscribed to mr shine thanks for being a special friend 
mouton opens a corner cabinet 
this is my daddys old accordion he bought it in 1918 for 
750 i dont know what it would cost today but i turned down 
2500 for it 
</TEXT>
