<TEXT>
playwright peter barnes recalls that about 10 
years ago critics were complaining about the length of his plays 
in frustration he tried radio he liked it 
barnes is not alone in writing regularly for both stage and 
radio the list includes such names as tom stoppard arnold wesker 
and harold pinter 
not only does radio offer exposure it attracts big names 
barnes wrote for radio one of the late laurence oliviers last 
roles no end to dreaming his radio work has enjoyed the 
luxury of talent such as dame peggy ashcroft paul scofield and sir 
john gielgud 
with the notable exception of david mamet few major playwrights 
in the united states bother with radio drama but several 
expatriate american writers have found a hospitable environment on 
the british airwaves 
craig warner a 25yearold american based in london has had 
three radio dramas produced by the british broadcasting corp he 
says he has now written more radio plays than he ever heard 
broadcast when he was in his native los angeles 
warners by where the old shed used to be won a giles cooper 
award as one of the five best radio dramas of the past year 
for many the bbc and radio drama are synonymous besides 
serials and soap operas the network produces an average of 500 
radio plays a year 
two commercial stations radio clyde in scotland and lbc 
crownfm in london also program radio drama 
finlay welsh drama producer at radio clyde acknowledges that 
audiences and financial returns are small 
however he said in an interview its very important that an 
independent radio station not simply produce news and music 
programs but also make a definite and deliberate contribution to 
writing and acting 
radio dramas heyday dates back to dylan thomass under 
milkwood perhaps the bestknown radio play ever it lasted until 
the mid1960s 
those were the days when the theater was under censorship there 
was no alternative fringe theater to pick up the slack 
the very important thing is to nurture writers says john 
tydeman head of the bbc radio drama department pinter still 
writes tom stoppard is writing a pla for us they can say things 
in a certain way on radio and we are discovering new people all 
the time 
some are first surprised then delighted to find themselves 
writing for radio 
peter barnes series barness people began on bbc radio 3 in 
1980 
radio was a ball because they just asked i delivered and 
they put it on he says 
barnes notes that radio plays are made in three or four days 
compared with the eight years it took for his awardwinning 1985 
