<TEXT>
the warren beattymadonna movie may be 
attracting a lot of hoopla but dick tracy is no newcomer to the 
screen 
tracy purists may prefer dick tracy meets gruesome circa 
1947 in which the fabled flatfoot does battle with the great boris 
karlorff or maybe dick tracy vs cueball a lowbudget 1946 
flick in which the detective takes on a bald smuggler 
then there are two other rko features of the mid1940s that 
starred ralph byrd or morgan conway as the steeljawed hawknosed 
sleuth or see dick tracy as an fbi agent in dick tracys 
gmen a 1939 yarn with byrd chasing the evil zarnoff 
if you have the patience you could watch four serials dating 
from 1937 to 1941 with byrd as chester goulds comicstrip hero 
beattys rediscovery of dick tracy follows the pattern of recent 
hollywood times filmmakers have been exploiting longestablish 
characters of comic strips and books giving them a modern look for 
todays audiences batman is the biggest success story thus far 
created by bob kane in 1939 batman flew onto the big screen 
with serials in 1943 and 1949 the sensation of the 196567 
television series led to a 1966 feature also starring adam west 
and burt ward last year a hypedup batman starring jack 
nicholson and michael keaton proved a huge moneymaker 
superman dates back to 1940s serials a 1951 quickie 
superman and the mole men and the subsequent tv series starring 
george reeves christopher reeve took over the cape in the 1978 
epic superman it was a huge hit followed by three sequels 
with diminishing results 
little orphan annie first hit the screen in 1932 with mitzi 
green as the carrottopped waif then gloryoskee annie 
became a hit broadway musical in the 1970s its success was 
repeated in a 1982 movie directed by john huston of all people 
and starring albert finney carol burnett and bernadette peters 
not all comic heroes and heroines have done as well in recent 
years flash gordon was an expensive failure in 1980 helping 
along the eventual collapse of dino de laurentiis american 
enterprise popeye bombed in 1980 despite the best efforts of 
robin williams to imitate the oneeye spinach fancier brenda 
starr with brooke shields as the resourceful reporter remains 
on the shelf after three years partly because of legal tangles 
brenda starr was made by new world pictures which has since 
gone out of business there are disputes over new worlds assets 
and whether or not the movie will be released depends largely on 
how the disputes are resolved but the film has appeared in some 
overseas countries 
motion pictures and comic strips were born at about the same 
time and almost immediately began their association hearst 
cartoonist winsor mccay drew his little nemo for the screen in 
1911 and followed with gertie the dinosaur in 1914 krazy 
kat bringing up father and the katzenjammer kids were 
other early movie cartoons 
comics also contributed characters for live action ella 
cinders colleen moore 1922 tillie the toiler marion 
davies 1927 skippy jackie cooper 1930 harold teen 
arthur lake 1934 and joe palooka stewart erwin 1934 and 
another version in 1946 with joe kirkwood plus sequels 
serials which hollywood ground out from 1930 to 1950 were 
ideal for telling comic book stories they included archie 
captain marvel flash gordon jungle jim mandrake 
the magician talespin tommy brick bradford and terry 
and the pirates 
for 10 years starting in 1938 arthur lake and penny singleton 
annually appeared in two blondie films as sandwichloving 
dagwood bumstead and his dizzy wife after his tarzan days were 
over johnny weissmuller made 12 quickies as jungle jim from 
1948 to 1955 
after scoring as a musical on broadway lil abner came to 
the screen in 1959 with all its dogpatch characters intact 
prince valiant put robert wagner in a pageboy wig in 1954 
bill mauldins dogface soldiers willie and joe appeared in the 1951 
up front and did a sequel back at the front 
racier comics also have made it to the screen modesty 
blaise monica vitti 1966 barbarella jane fonda 1968 
and the only xrated cartoon movie fritz the cat in 1971 
