laredo mca steve wariner 
 
steve wariners easygoing laredo travels over some familiar 
country ground but comes up a winner on the strength of 
aboveaverage songs and the singers ability to convey that he 
clearly enjoys the material 
using three producers wariner shifts comfortably from midtempo 
ballads to lite swing maintaining a pleasant groove that 
falters only when he indulges in the sappy sentimentality of i 
wanna go back a needless lament for the good ol days 
wariner a staple on the country charts knows what makes a hit 
and almost everything else on laredo sounds groomed for the 
radio precious thing a bluesy love song the tearjerkers 
shes in love and there for awhile and the clever the 
domino theory appear likely candidates to receive airplay 
the band is tight the piano playing is superb throughout four 
keyboardists are credited and the digital recording is clear and 
uncluttered but not cold 
all in all a safe likable album if you have to go down the 
middle of the road steve wariners not a bad guy to have along as 
a rider 
by marc rice associated press writer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
dog city grudge crack the sky 
 
with dog city crack the sky is guilty of one of rock n 
rolls deadly sins wrapping politically charged messages in dull 
plodding music 
this band has a lot to say but who can pay attention to the 
words when the music is putting them to sleep and despite the 
bombast here who can stay awake through this set 
this from a band that knows better 
never a household name crack the sky does enjoy some cult 
status largely on the strength of its 1975 debut which 
successfully mixed john palumbos delightfully bizarre songwriting 
with quirky imaginative guitarbased rock 
none of that here palumbos lyrical sights are on the nations 
social ills the homeless drug abuse violence but his words 
are lost in a mix of leaden hardrock cliches even if you agree 
with what hes saying you may find yourself wanting to join the 
other side 
only on mr president in which a childrens choir makes a 
plea for the government to do something about the homeless does 
the music break away from the muck its not nearly enough though 
to salvage this dog of an album 
by marc rice associated press writer 
</TEXT>
