<TEXT>
grace lai stumbled into her artistic passion but 
she cant afford to stumble now 
lai spends much of her time 30 stories or more above the ground 
sometimes near open walls and elevator shafts just to get the 
right perspective for her paintings 
hardhat on head she totes her studio on a handcart painting 
watercolors of chicagos changing skyline and the workers who 
change it 
shes been working at the north state street site of the 
american medical associations new headquarters for about two 
years watching excavators welders steelworkers cement workers 
plumbers electrical contractors carpenters tilesetters 
pipefitters and more 
no one has ever tried to document what they do lai says 
this is something they can take home and show their wives and 
say look i really do work 
lai 62 and her husband harry operated acme studios at 
various chicago locations for 25 years until his death in 1985 she 
then decided to return to school and try to support herself with 
her art 
she sketched her first construction site in 1985 it was on her 
first day back in art school when her bus dropped her at the 
42story office tower at 190 n lasalle the first chicago building 
designed by the architect philip johnson 
transit schedules forced her to arrive two hours early for class 
at the american academy of art and she filled the time sketching 
several weeks later the chief site inspector noticed her liked 
her work and made her the official artist for the construction 
site 
the current building is the third site shes painted between 
johnsons building and her current site she climbed and painted 
the 50story tower at 35 w wacker drive that houses the leo 
burnett co advertising agency 
before she found her passion for painting construction sites 
she used the only subject of which she could think 
i used to just sketch people on the buses back and forth from 
visiting my father in the nursing home she says but it was a 
chancy thing if people found out you were sketching them and 
didnt like it you took your life in your hands but most of them 
were delighted 
her original watercolors sell for 400 to 500 she has 8by 
10inch prints made of each one and sells the prints to workers for 
15 to 40 she sells enough to get by she says 
she leaves space around the construction scenes in many of her 
works which she fills with portraits of individual workers or 
crews the workers often pose briefly during their coffee breaks 
when are you gonna do me gracie one worker asks any 
time she says they agree on a painting and a time and part 
company each expressing thanks 
john buck co and millerklutznickdavisgray co partners in 
the building plan to show her works at the buildings grand 
opening tentatively scheduled in august 
lai will have 25 to 30 fullsize watercolors ready all showing 
different phases of construction she hopes the show will bring 
recognition and a wider audience 
it will be her first show outside the pallet and chisel a group 
of chicago artists with a studio in the downtown loop who combine 
their efforts to promote local art her paintings now are available 
only at her inhome company advertising art and at the city of 
chicago store in the loop 
success for me would be being respected by fellow artists 
this may end up affording me a living but i dont want to turn out 
garbage she says 
most importantly i want to be an artist it doesnt have to 
be in construction id like to go into a paper mill or an atomic 
plant things people hear about and never see you have to be 
halfinsane to do it but my gosh can you find anything more 
exciting 
the excitement and potential danger of being hundreds of 
feet above the ground has never caused her any trouble says lai 
who signs a release at each site a contractor involved with each 
site has insured her under his company policy 
my only problems are off the site last year i spent four 
months on crutches because i was doing aerobics and i landed wrong 
so aerobics can go ill walk she said 
however the time on crutches was even helpful 
after i came back my painting changed entirely i became a 
lot more thoughtful i did whole scenes instead of just throwing 
things together i think it was being away for so long it made me 
realize what i was missing 
construction workers help her stay out of the way she says 
you kind of sense when things are starting to move and 
usually somebody will come by and say gracie scat she 
laughed again 
lai worked in december when she had to add alcohol to her paints 
to keep them from freezing and had to cut the fingers out of her 
gloves on her drawing hand to handle her pens and brushes 
and she didnt quit when her friends told her she wouldnt 
finish art school or when her classmates began placing bets on 
when shed drop out she graduated last year 
her tenacity has provided her with a living experience and 
friendships 
i know so many of my friends who say nobody ever comes to 
see me youve got to out and meet the world 
</TEXT>
