<TEXT>
tektronix inc announced tuesday it will 
lay off about 1300 employees as part of a restructuring designed 
to offset the electronics manufacturers financial problems 
under the restructuring the 44yearold company said it plans 
to sell or close some of its test and measurement operations and 
nontelevision communications businesses 
the layoffs will reduce the companys employment to about 13000 
by august tektronix said in a statement 
these steps are part of a broad effort to place tek on a solid 
financial footing for the long term said robert lundeen 
chairman and chief executive officer 
the restructuring and layoffs will result in a onetime charge 
of about 70 million in the fourth quarter ended may 26 the 
company said 
tektronix has suffered net losses or only marginal profits in 
recent quarters on flat or declining sales in the quarter ended in 
march the loss was a record 245 million the companys annual 
sales are about 14 billion 
longtime president david p friedley resigned in april at the 
boards request and lundeen assumed the title of chief executive 
officer 
the company declined to specify which businesses will be sold 
but said the process would begin immediately 
tektronix also said it is exploring the possibility of 
partnerships to enhance the market position and performance of its 
visual systems television equipment unit 
tektronix also said it has ended discussions with sony corp 
concerning the possible sale of the companys grass valley group 
subsidiary 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

