<DOCNO> AP900529-0226 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
recent sharp increases in the prices of food 
staples have led several states to cut food allotments or drop 
people from welfare rolls 
the cost of milk orange juice cereal eggs and infant formula 
has risen 8 percent in the first half of this fiscal year four 
times the rate predicted by the federal food and nutrition service 
the new york times reported today 
the price increases have stretched the 21 billion that the 
federal women infants and children program spends on 45 million 
new and expectant mothers 
as a result the states which administer the program have had 
to either reduce the food allotment reduce the number of 
participants or both 
federal officials said they did not know how many people had 
been affected by the cuts the times said 
f phillip shanholtzer spokesman for the food and nutrition 
service said the inflation has outstripped everyones 
predictions 
officials blamed the price increases such as a 133 percent 
rise in the cost of orange juice and 59 percent for cereals on 
natural effects such as the drought of 1988 and the december freeze 
in florida 
texas and missouri are not accepting new cases both states said 
children who show no signs of clinical malnutrition will be cut 
from the program 
new york will try to cut its caseload by 20000 to 360000 
while connecticut no longer allows use of federal funds to buy 
orange juice suggesting instead that mothers buy apple or 
pineapple juice which cost less 
illinois officials however say their state is an exception to 
the national problem and will not have to cut any of its 162000 
recipients according to the chicago tribune which also reported 
on friday on cuts in the wic program 
congress has proposed a 150 million increase in the program for 
next year that money was meant to strengthen the program but now 
officials hope it will be enough to stay even 
the wic program provides poor families with food vouchers it is 
open to pregnant women those who have just given birth and 
children 
it serves 1 million women 14 million infants and 21 million 
other children under age 5 or about onethird of all babies born 
in the united states 
during the 1980s when other welfare programs were cut wic was 
spared because federal studies said it saved lives reduced infant 
mortality and prevented illness thereby sparing future expense to 
medicaid 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

