<DOCNO> AP900529-0231 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a top us trade official on tuesday appealed to 
other rich nations to give a push to trade talks stalled by a 
dispute between the united states and european nations over 
government payments to farmers 
a window of opportunity is now us trade representative 
carla hills said a day before the opening of highlevel discussions 
by trade and finance chiefs of two dozen industrialized nations 
the possibilities are profound she said it just is going 
to take the political will to do it 
the officials are attending the annual meeting of the 
organization for economic cooperation and development they were 
expected to focus on the uruguay round talks an ambitious effort 
to revamp the world trading system 
the negotiations which involve about 100 nations are designed 
to reduce barriers to trade in agriculture textiles and other 
manufactured goods and in services such as banking and investment 
the bargaining began in uruguay in 1986 and is due to end in 
december but a fight between the united states and the 12nation 
european community over agricultural subsidies has raised concern 
the talks could end in failure 
the united states wants the ec also known as the common market 
to end import barriers and domestic and export farm subsidies that 
distort trade us officials estimate that ending the costly 
subsidies could boost us farm exports by 11 billion annually 
the common market give its farmers subsidies through guaranteed 
prices for many crops it also assists exporters so more expensive 
european farm products can compete with lower prices on the world 
market 
the community argues it has begun trimming farm aid but contends 
it cannot scrap the program entirely in 1988 european leaders 
adopted a plan limiting the maximum annual amount of expenditure on 
price guarantees over five years 
us officials have said the measures were not enough to fix 
what they deem a fundamentally flawed system 
agriculture is a key to the success of the round so that the 
europeans are going to have to decide whether they want a 
successful round mrs hills said 
she said about 1 trillion worth of commerce was not covered by 
international rules without regulations countries can use a 
variety of tactics some considered unfair by trading partners 
to sell their goods or protect them from competitors 
mrs hills said that if we dont get a deal in agriculture 
were not going to build the rules we need in these areas where 
there are no rules at all 
its just time that we do have rules for without rules we are 
a lawless international trading community she said 
the flow of textiles for instance is controlled by a network 
of tariffs and quotas not by the multinational trading system 
the uruguay round talks are held under the auspices of the 
general agreement on tariffs and trade gatt is a forum and an 
agreement for promoting freer trade 
officials want to move talks along so lowerlevel negotiators 
can reach preliminary agreement in at least some of 15 areas under 
discussion at a july 23 session in geneva switzerland 
oecd members are australia austria belgium britain canada 
denmark finland france greece iceland ireland italy japan 
luxembourg the netherlands new zealand norway portugal spain 
sweden switzerland turkey the united states and west germany 
</TEXT>
