<TEXT>
the supreme court agreed monday to decide 
whether state laws that interfere unconstitutionally with 
interstate businesses also may violate federal civil rights law 
at issue in the nebraska case is whether states can be forced to 
pay lawyer fees and other legal expenses for businesses that 
challenge a states discriminatory taxes 
the case stems from an ohio truckers challenge of a nebraska 
truck tax mark dennis the owner of dennis trucking in royalton 
ohio sued the nebraska department of motor vehicles in 1984 over 
taxes imposed on truckers from states that imposed certain types of 
taxes on nebraskabased trucking businesses 
the taxes which are no longer in effect were imposed on trucks 
from arizona arkansas idaho nevada new york ohio oregon 
pennsylvania and wyoming 
nebraska courts ruled that the state tax interfered 
impermissibly with interstate commerce state officials were barred 
from collecting the taxes but the courts refused to treat dennis 
suit as a civil rights case which would have entitled him to 
recoup lawyers fees and other expenses 
the case is dennis vs higgins 891555 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

