<TEXT>
east germany plans to speed 
privatization of its industry as the nation lays foundations for a 
switch to capitalism its economics minister said tuesday 
economics minister gerhard pohl said only 180 of about 8000 
stateowned industries have been converted into publicly held 
companies so far 
if things continue like this it will take five years to 
reach total privatization pohl told reporters in bonn after 
meeting with west german economics minister helmut haussmann 
pohl said the east german parliament is to approve a legal 
framework by october to quicken the process he said incentives 
were planned for potential investors in now stateowned 
enterprises but he did not elaborate 
west germany has been pressuring east germany to quicken 
privatization as a source of revenue for economic reconstruction 
the two german states are to become a single economic entity as of 
july 2 
west germany will provide massive financial backing to start the 
possibly painful transformation of east germanys centrally planned 
economy into one based on freemarket principles 
for its part east germany has pledged to start selling off 
stateowned property to produce its own contributions for economic 
reconstruction there are fears privatization could result in 
eliminating many ailing businesses unable to withstand competition 
pohl and haussmann discussed plans to build a layer of small and 
mediumsized companies to form the backbone of the newly 
restructured east german economy 
pohl said his government plans legislation to increase fivefold 
the number of trainee positions available in industry starting in 
september 
he said it is too soon to say how many people will lose their 
jobs as uncompetitive industrial companies go out of business in 
the economic merger pohl said about 1 million people will have to 
be retrained under the new order 
</TEXT>
