express it forcefully he said 
kondrusev and victor tutelyan an official with the soviet 
academy of medical scientists spoke at the opening of the 
international conference on food safety at michigan state 
university 
tutelyan said some meat milk and potatoes from a 
6200squaremile area near chernobyl are still contaminated with 
radiation he said 4 million people live in the area 
it will be a long time before it will be possible to obtain 
milk that meets current safety standards and is acceptable for 
use he said 
high radiation levels began showing up in soviet milk two or 
three days after the april 26 1986 explosion at the nuclear power 
station in chernobyl about 80 miles north of kiev 
two jetlike emissions of radioactive material spewed into the 
air followed for 10 days by a cloud of radioactive gases tutelyan 
said 
he said soviet officials attempted to protect the public by 
moving cattle into barns so that they would not graze in pastures 
contaminated by the fallout 
some citizens rejected the governments countermeasures nearly 
30 people mostly elderly farmers insisted on leaving their milk 
cows outdoors to graze on contaminated grass tutelyan said the 
farmers who were 70 or older decided not to worry about 
developing cancer in 20 years 
meat contaminated with radiation was buried in a 20mile zone 
around chernobyl but tutelyan said new technology has been 
developed to decontaminate meat 
he also said milk can be made into butter because the 
radioactive contaminants are concentrated in the water portion of 
the milk and can be separated in 1986 20 percent to 30 percent of 
milk meat greens and fruits produced near chernobyl had to be 
discarded he said 
 
